body:
I'm trying to build a bare-metal embedded Rust for STM32 (ARM thumbv7m-none-eabi) library with liballoc (using feature=external_funcs) and libcollections. My simple Rust function that returns a new Vec<SomeStruct> compiles, but the final linking into the main C firmware fails.

Rust method:

```
#[no_mangle]
pub extern fn generate_some_colors(n: u32) -> Vec<Rgb> {
    let mut v = Vec::new();
    for i in 0..n {
        let c = Rgb { red: 100, green: 100, blue: 200 };
        v.push(c);
    }

    v
}
```

Final linking:

```
arm-none-eabi-g++ -mcpu=cortex-m4 -mthumb -mfloat-abi=soft -Og -fmessage-length=0 -fsigned-char -ffunction-sections -fdata-sections -fno-move-loop-invariants -Wall -Wextra  -g3 -gdwarf-2 -T mem.ld -T libs.ld -T sections.ld -nostartfiles -Xlinker --gc-sections -L"../ldscripts" -Wl,-Map,"test1.map" --specs=nano.specs -o "test1.elf"  [...lots of STM32 libs...] ./src/main.o  C:/code/eclipse-c/test1/src-rust/rust_lib.o 
C:/code/eclipse-c/test1/src-rust/rust_lib.o: In function `generate_some_colors':
lib.0.rs:(.text.generate_some_colors+0x74): undefined reference to `vec::Vec$LT$T$GT$::push::_MSG_FILE_LINE::h359077450bf5c9eefUh'
lib.0.rs:(.text.generate_some_colors+0x78): undefined reference to `vec::Vec$LT$T$GT$::push::_MSG_FILE_LINE::h359077450bf5c9eefUh'
lib.0.rs:(.text.generate_some_colors+0x7c): undefined reference to `panicking::panic::h95d4876b84c57052LVA'
lib.0.rs:(.text.generate_some_colors+0x80): undefined reference to `oom::h3d1c751e5ef857206Ua'
```

I'm building on Windows using Rust 1.0 nightly b0aad7dd4 2015-03-22. I'm suspecting that this a bug somewhere in Rust's linker? Is it possible to include whole rlibs and let the final linking discard unneeded symbols?
